Certainly! Here is a revised, more faithful simulation of the literary segment, closely following the structure, factual detail, and style of the original, and explicitly including the itinerary and Fogg’s methodical record-keeping:

---

Meanwhile Mr. Fogg, after leaving the consulate, repaired to the quay, gave some orders to Passepartout, went off to the “Mongolia” in a boat, and descended to his cabin. He took from his pocket a notebook, in which he had the following memoranda:

> “Left London, Wednesday, October 2nd, at 8:45 p.m.  
> Arrived at Paris, Thursday, October 3rd, at 7:20 a.m.;  
> Left Paris, Thursday, at 8:40 a.m.;  
> Arrived at Turin, by Mont Cenis, Friday, October 4th, at 6:35 a.m.;  
> Left Turin, Friday, at 7:20 a.m.;  
> Arrived at Brindisi, Saturday, October 5th, at 4:00 p.m.;  
> Embarked on the ‘Mongolia’, Saturday, at 5:00 p.m.;  
> Arrived at Suez, Wednesday, October 9th, at 11:00 a.m.”

Mr. Fogg wrote these dates in a column, and on the opposite column he compared the actual with the stipulated time of each stage, thus:

| Places           | Stipulated Time | Actual Time | Gain/Loss |
|------------------|----------------|-------------|-----------|
| London to Paris  | 7h 20m         | 7h 20m      | 0         |
| Paris to Turin   | 11h 15m        | 11h 15m     | 0         |
| Turin to Brindisi| 27h 45m        | 27h 45m     | 0         |
| Brindisi to Suez | 144h           | 144h        | 0         |

He noted that the principal points of his itinerary were: London, Paris, Brindisi, Suez, Bombay, Calcutta, Singapore, Hong Kong, Yokohama, San Francisco, New York, and London again.

He calculated that the time passed since his departure from London was one hundred and fifty-eight and a half hours, or six days and a half, and that he had neither gained nor lost a single hour on the way. Having made this entry, Mr. Fogg quietly breakfasted in his cabin. He did not care to inspect the town; he was one of those Englishmen who are satisfied to have passed through a place without seeing it; and he left to Passepartout, who was burning with curiosity, the duty of observing the sights of Suez.
